  1. Change the data type of popularity to a factor in the data frame songs and create a boxplot of the distribution of duration_ms by popularity. Discuss the distribution of durations_ms by popularity
songs$popularity<- as.factor(songs$popularity)
ggplot(songs, aes(x=popularity, y=duration_ms))+
  geom_boxplot(fill="#FFF0F5")+
  labs(title="Distribution of Duration by Popularity", x="Popularity", y="Duration (ms)")+
  theme(text=element_text(size=18))

Most of the songs, no matter the popularity, have a similar duration. The medians are all around 200000ms. There are many outliers, but there seem to be more in the songs with lower popularity.

  1. What do you find based on the boxplots in Questions 4 and 5.

For the duration boxplots, since there are more large outliers in the low popularity groups, this might mean that longer songs are less popular and shorter songs are more popular. For the instrumentalness boxplots, the least popular songs have a higher instrumentalness which means they have more instrumentals and less vocals. The most popular songs are full of vocals without instrumentals.

  1. Group the data frame songs by track_artist and find the correspond median, Q3 - Q1 for danceability, energy, speechiness, acousticness, instrumentalness, liveness, valence and counts for each track_artist. Save the result to unpopular_artists and sort the data frame via the descending order of counts. Print the top 10 unpopular artists and the corresponding information in unpopular_artists. Summaize your finding based on the result shown here.
unpopular_artists<-songs %>%
  group_by(track_artist) %>%
  summarize(med_danceability=median(danceability),
            med_energy=median(energy),
            med_speechiness=median(speechiness),
            med_acousticness=median(acousticness),
            med_instrumentalness=median(instrumentalness),
            med_liveness=median(liveness),
            med_valence=median(valence),
            counts=n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(counts))

  1. Create two new variables: instrumentalness_status and boringness in the data frame songs. The variable instrumentalness_status has the value “High” for the songs that their instrumentalness is higher than the mean instrumentalness, otherwise it is “Low”. The variable boringness is calculated by boringness = loudness + tempo + (energy*100) + (danceability*100) Hint: You can use this command ifelse(condition, value1, value2), it assigns value 1 to the new variable when the condition is TRUE, otherwise it assign value 2 to the variable.
songs<- songs %>%
  mutate(instrumentalness_status=
           ifelse(instrumentalness>mean(instrumentalness), "High", "Low"),
    boringness=loudness + tempo + (energy*100) + (danceability*100))
  1. Create a bar plot that shows the conditional distribution of instrumentalness_status by the popularity of songs. Comment on your barplot.
ggplot(songs, aes(x=popularity, fill=instrumentalness_status))+
  geom_bar()+
  labs(title="Distribution of Instrumentalness Status by Popularity", x="Popularity", y="Number of Songs")+
  theme(text=element_text(size=15))

There are mostly songs with low popularity ratings in this dataset. All of the popularity categories have more low instrumentalness than high instrumentalness songs. There is a little spike in frequency at popularity 13-15, but we can see that there are very few mid and high popularity songs in the dataset.

  1. Create a boxplot that shows the distribution of boringness by the popularity of songs. Comment on your boxplot. What did you find based on the boxplot. Hint: You should recall how this variable was calculated.
ggplot(songs, aes(x=popularity, y=boringness))+
  geom_boxplot(fill="#C1FFC1")+
  labs(title="Distribution of Boringness by Popularity", x="Popularity", y="Boringness")+
  theme(text=element_text(size=18))

Because boringness was created by adding up loudness, tempo, energy, and danceability, I am going to assume that a high boringness value actually means a song is less boring and a low boringness value means a song is more boring. This would mean that most songs in this dataset are not very boring. The median is similar for all popularity and is between 200 and 300. There are small outliers, the most and smallest belong to the least popular songs. This would mean that the least popular songs are most boring which makes sense.
